  "local_port": 37360,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the process to get a brand name trademarked in India?",
  "response": "Trademarking a brand name in India involves several steps to ensure legal protection and exclusive rights to the brand. Here\u2019s a detailed process:\n\n### 1. **Trademark Search**\n   - **Objective**: Ensure the brand name is unique and not already registered.\n   - **Process**: Conduct a search on the **Trademark Public Search** database available on the [Indian Trademark Registry\u2019s website](https://ipindiaonline.gov.in/).\n\n### 2. **Preparing the Application**\n   - **Details Required**:\n     - Applicant\u2019s name and address.\n     - Brand name/logo to be trademarked.\n     - Class of goods or services (as per the **Trademark Classifications** or **Nice Classification**).\n     - Description of the brand name or logo.\n   - **Documents Required**:\n     - Identity proof of the applicant (e.g., PAN card, Aadhaar, passport).\n     - Address proof of the applicant.\n     - Logo or brand name in digital format (if applicable).\n\n### 3. **Filing the Application**\n   - **Where to File**: Online via the [IP India Portal](https://ipindiaonline.gov.in/) or offline at the nearest **Trademark Registry Office**.\n   - **Form**: **Form TM-A** (Application for Trademark Registration).\n   - **Fees**: \u20b94,500\u2013\u20b99,500 per class (depending on whether the applicant is an individual, startup, or company).\n   - **Auctionality**: You can choose to file for a single class or multiple classes of goods/services.\n\n### 4. **Examination by the Trademark Office**\n   - **Timeline**: Within 1\u20132 months of filing.\n   - **Process**: The Trademark Examiner reviews the application and issues an **Examination Report**.\n   - **Possible Outcomes**:\n     - Accepted without objections.\n     - Objections raised (e.g., similarity to existing trademarks).\n   - **Responding to Objections**: If objections are raised, a response must be filed within **30 days** with supporting documents and arguments.\n\n### 5. **Publication in the Trademark Journal**\n   - **Publication**: If the application is accepted, it is published in the **Trademark Journal**.\n   - **Purpose**: Allows the public to view and oppose the trademark if they believe it infringes on their rights.\n   - **Opposition Period**: 4 months from the date of publication.\n\n### 6. **Opposition Handling (if applicable)**\n   - If there is **no opposition**, the trademark proceeds to registration.\n   - If there **is opposition**, the applicant must file a counter-statement and engage in legal proceedings.\n\n### 7. **Trademark Registration**\n   - **Timeline**: 6\u201312 months (if no objections or oppositions).\n   - **Process**: The Trademark Registry issues a **Certificate of Registration**.\n   - **Validity**: 10 years from the date of filing.\n\n### 8. **Renewal**\n   - **Timeline**: Trademark must be renewed every **10 years**.\n   - **Process**: File **Form TM-R** and pay the renewal fee.\n\n### Additional Notes:\n- **TM Symbol**: You can use the **\u2122 symbol** as soon as the application is filed if the trademark is unregistered.\n- **\u00ae Symbol**: You can use the **\u00ae symbol** only after the trademark is officially registered.\n\n### Professional Assistance:\n- Consider hiring a **trademark attorney** or **IP agent** to ensure compliance with legal requirements and handle the process efficiently.\n\nBy following these steps, you can successfully trademark your brand name in India and protect it from unauthorized use.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
